issue.title: ONNX model gets much slower on rel-0.5.0 compared to rel-0.4.0

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
The same model takes much longer to run on ONNX Runtime rel-0.5.0 compares to running on rel-0.4.0

**Urgency**
None

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): 18.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: 0.5.0
- Python version: 3.6.9
- Visual Studio version (if applicable):
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): gcc (Ubuntu 7.4.0-1ubuntu1~18.04.1) 7.4.0
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10
- GPU model and memory: TITAN V

**To Reproduce**
- Run in docker image built from [Dockerfile.cuda](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/dockerfiles/Dockerfile.cuda) in proper release version branch
- After unzipping the file from link in "additional context", run `perf_client_decoder_onnx_runtime.py` script, and latency will be printed once the script is finished

**Expected behavior**
The latency should be the same as running on rel-0.4.0, but it is more than 10x slower:
rel-0.5.0
```
5.224515144220607
Latency average (seconds) = 5.2252
Latency cl 50 (seconds) = 5.2356
Latency cl 90 (seconds) = 5.3368
Latency cl 95 (seconds) = 5.3922
Latency cl 99 (seconds) = 5.6429
Latency cl 100 (seconds) = 6.1242
```
rel-0.4.0
```
0.2804932994043042
Latency average (seconds) = 0.2805
Latency cl 50 (seconds) = 0.2762
Latency cl 90 (seconds) = 0.2947
Latency cl 95 (seconds) = 0.2999
Latency cl 99 (seconds) = 0.3504
Latency cl 100 (seconds) = 0.5494
```
**Screenshots**
If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.

**Additional context**
Link to the model and client:
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1r_3nHM-bBR_lyiezfsJhPsoOSdN29Afb/view?usp=sharing

body:
@drapado, I'm having a similar issue. I haven't looked at your code yet, but are you using System.Numerics.Tensor.ToTensor() to convert your image floats into a tensor before you use NamedOnnxValue.CreateFromTensor()?

The ToTensor(), step, copying a flattened 720x720x3 array of floats to a Tensor, adds 80ms to my inference, while the CreateFromTensor() is very light and Inference.Session.Run() is seems around 2ms (GTX1070ti, Cuda). 

Perhaps Python has a more efficient way to transfer collections of floats/Numpy into a session. I'd personally like to see something like CreateFromArray or CreateFromEnumerable, since CreateFromTensor() doesn't copy and I can prepare a model to do the reshaping from within, but I understand that may not suit everyone.

Hi @faxu, any update on this issue?

Hi @YanYas,

are you getting 2 ms in session.run() with the model I uploaded in this issue? If so could you share the code you are using it to run it?

Thanks a lot!

Hi @drapado,

Sorry, I didn't test with your model before, but I can understand you being dissatisfied with the inference time. After learning to create the Tensor from new Memory<Float>(Array<float32> I got a decent speed up. But I still only managed 72ms with your model using c#/[Gamma](https://vvvv.org/blog/vvvv-gamma-2019.1-preview).
The GPU usage peaked and trothed between 36% and 85% (tested with GPUShark). I can make the code available if you want it, and you don;t mind doing some setup. It isn't a strictly c# project

body: @drapado @YanYas - have you tried the lastest 1.0 release of ORT and does this issue still persist? A few additional CUDA kernels have been added, and there are more in the master branch that'll be in the next release or you can build from source.
